<h1>To John Armstrong</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dear Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Mount Vernon Octr 10th 1773.</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Upon my return home from the Annapolis Races (from whence I wrote you, committing the Letter to the care of Captn McGachen of Baltimore Town, who assured me it should be forwarded the Week after) I receivd a Letter from Lord Dunmore our Governor, containing the following Paragraph, which I inclose for your information, agreeable to my promise.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0269-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0269-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<div class="quoteFT">
<div class="floatingText">
<p style="text-indent: 1em;">I last Post receivd yours of the 12th Instt (that is Septr) wherein you beg to be informed whether I propose granting Patents on the Ohio to such Officers &amp; Soldiers as claim under his Majestys Proclamation in 8ber 1763. I do not mean to grant any Patents on the Western Waters, as I do not <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">think</span> I am <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">at present</span> empowered so to do. I did indeed tell a poor old German Lieutt who was with me, and informed me he was very poor &amp; had ten Children that I <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">possibly</span> might grant him a Patent contiguous to that which he had under Mr Dinwiddies Proclamation, which I suppose is what may have given rise to the report you have heard.</p>
</div>
</div>
<p>I was suspicious, as I think I wrote you in my last, that the report of Lord Dunmores granting Patents was rather premature; for after declaring to the Officers of his own Government that, he did not conceive himself at liberty to Issue Patents for Lands on the Western Waters, I could scarce think he would change his opinion without giving them some intimation of it, either in a publick, or private manner; and yet, there are some words in his Letter (which I have markd) which seem to Imply an expectation at least of doing it. It remains therefore to be considered, whether the Officers claiming under his Majestys Proclamation of 1763 have<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0269-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0269-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> a better chance of securing their lands elsewhere; and if they have not, whether the known equity
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-09-02-pb-0346">[346]</span>
of their claims, the prevailing opinion that Bullet is proceeding by authority in the surveys he is now making, and the united endeavors of the officers to obtain patents for the lands actually surveyed, may not discourage other emigrants from settling thereon; and, in the end, induce government to comply with their just requisitions by fullfilling its own voluntary promises. I own it is a kind of lottery, and whether the chance of a prize is not worth the expense of a survey, is the point in question. As subjects and individuals of the community at large, we are at least upon a par with those who are occupying the country; but whether any of these pleas, under the present discouragements of government, will avail anything, is a mere matter of speculation, on which every person must exercise his own powers of reflection.</p>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0269-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter: a letter in the handwriting of the author ]">AL</abbr> (incomplete photocopy), Sotheby, Parke-Bernet catalog, no. 4389, item 43; 
<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford, ed. &lt;i&gt;The Writings of George Washington&lt;/i&gt;. 14 vols. New York, 188993. ]">Ford, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Writings of Washington</span></span>, 2:39495.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0269-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0269-fn-0001">1</a>
   
   <p>GW returned to Mount Vernon from Annapolis on 2 October. The letter dated 28 Sept. that he sent to Armstrong from Annapolis <span class="choice correction" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Corrected from 'has not been found' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2006-06-12]]&lt;/span&gt; ]">is listed and partially transcribed in Joseph Rubinstines catalog, no. 152, as to an unidentified correspondent</span>. The letter from Lord Dunmore which GW quotes here is dated 24 September. William McGachen was a sea captain with whom GW had had dealings for a number of years (see especially <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0157" class="document">GW to Robert Cary &amp; Co., 4 Oct. 1763</a>). GW later bought indentured servants from McGachen (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0384" class="document">McGachen to GW, 13 Mar. 1774</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-10-02-0034" class="document">GW to McGachen, 1 May 1774</a>). The latter part of this letter to Armstrong suggests that GW was writing in response to Armstrongs inquiry of <span class="choice correction" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Corrected from '11' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2008-10-02]]&lt;/span&gt; ]">17</span> Aug. about the likelihood of Dunmores issuing patents to ex-officers of the Pennsylvania forces for the lands on the Ohio being surveyed by Thomas Bullitts party (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0188&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-09-02-0188-fn-0006#GEWN-02-09-02-0188-fn-0006" class="document"><span class="choice correction" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Corrected from 'Thomas' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2008-08-28]]&lt;/span&gt; ]">John</span> Connelly to GW, 29 June 1773, n.6</a>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0269-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0269-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The remainder of this letter is taken from the printed version in Ford.</p>

</div>
</div>
